In 20 years, many more Gambians have passed through the educational systems of this country than at any time before, hence Gambia will become a more developed country in the next 20 years than it is today. Yet none of these are synonymous with the right to freedom of speech. Freedom of speech must be about more than what Gambians are allowed to read in the newspapers today. Indeed, for Gambia to make real progress we need a real conversation about what Gambia must do to enjoy the most fundamental human right. Our definition of democracy must go beyond elections and elections must become means to an end and not the end itself.

THE AUTHOR

Honi Effanga, is a lecturer in Law, University of Dundee, Scotland and author of The Struggle for Freedom in The Gambia, 1950-1994.

Constitutionalism "as important as democracy" argues Gambian opposition leader

By Aminata S. Kargbo/APC Secretary General

Professor Dr Isatou Touray the APC leader has stated that "Constitutionalism is as important as democracy." Professor Touray made these remarks recently when she paid a courtesy visit to the Chief Justice in Freetown the capital City of Sierra Leone.
